# Core Types and Interfaces

The core package defines the foundational data types used throughout intentc. It is a leaf dependency with no imports from other intentc packages. All other packages depend on core.

## Package

`github.com/pboueri/intentc/src/core`

## Types

### Intent

Represents a parsed .ic file. Contains both the structured frontmatter metadata and the raw markdown body.

Fields:
- `Name` (string) - Feature identifier, matches directory name.
- `Version` (int) - Schema version from frontmatter.
- `DependsOn` ([]string) - List of feature dependency names.
- `Tags` ([]string) - Categorization tags.
- `Profile` (string) - Optional named agent profile for building this target. Empty means use the default or CLI-specified profile.
- `Content` (string) - The full raw markdown body (everything after the frontmatter).
- `FilePath` (string) - Absolute path to the source .ic file.

### Validation

Represents a single validation definition extracted from an .icv file's frontmatter.

Fields:
- `Name` (string) - Unique validation identifier.
- `Type` (ValidationType) - The validation type enum.
- `Hidden` (bool) - Whether the agent should see this validation.
- `Parameters` (map[string]any) - Type-specific parameters (path, command, rubric, etc.).

### ValidationType

A string enum with values:
- `file_check`
- `folder_check`
- `command_check`
- `llm_judge`

### ValidationFile

Represents a parsed .icv file containing multiple validations.

Fields:
- `Target` (string) - Feature name this validates.
- `Version` (int) - Schema version.
- `JudgeProfile` (string) - Optional named agent profile for llm_judge validations in this file. When set, the LLM judge uses a different agent than the one that built the target, preventing self-grading bias. Empty means use the build agent.
- `Validations` ([]Validation) - The validation definitions.
- `FilePath` (string) - Absolute path to the source .icv file.

### Target

Represents a buildable unit: an intent paired with its validations and resolved dependencies.

Fields:
- `Name` (string) - Feature identifier.
- `Intent` (*Intent) - The parsed intent.
- `Validations` ([]*ValidationFile) - Associated validation files.
- `Dependencies` ([]*Target) - Resolved dependency targets (pointers, not names).
- `Status` (TargetStatus) - Current build status.

### TargetStatus

A string enum with values:
- `pending` - Not yet built.
- `building` - Currently being built.
- `built` - Successfully built.
- `failed` - Build failed.
- `outdated` - Built but spec has changed since.

### BuildResult

Represents the outcome of a single target build.

Fields:
- `Target` (string) - Target name.
- `GenerationID` (string) - Unique build identifier (e.g., `gen-1234567890`).
- `Success` (bool) - Whether the build succeeded.
- `Error` (string) - Error message if failed (not an error type - must be serializable).
- `GeneratedAt` (time.Time) - When the build completed.
- `Files` ([]string) - List of files created or modified.
- `OutputDir` (string) - The output directory used for this build.

### ValidationResult

Represents the outcome of running a single validation.

Fields:
- `ValidationName` (string) - Which validation was run.
- `Passed` (bool) - Whether it passed.
- `Message` (string) - Human-readable result message.
- `Details` ([]string) - Additional detail lines.
- `Severity` (string) - "error" or "warning".

### AgentProfile

Represents a named, reusable agent configuration that bundles provider, prompt templates, tools, and skills into a single unit. Agent profiles are defined in `.intentc/config.yaml` and referenced by name.

Fields:
- `Name` (string) - Profile identifier (e.g., "default", "fast", "review").
- `Provider` (string) - Agent provider name: "claude", "codex", "cli". Determines which agent implementation is used.
- `Command` (string) - For CLI provider: the shell command to invoke. Ignored for built-in providers.
- `CLIArgs` ([]string) - Additional CLI arguments passed to the agent command.
- `Timeout` (time.Duration) - Per-invocation timeout. Default 5m.
- `Retries` (int) - Number of retries on failure. Default 3.
- `RateLimit` (time.Duration) - Delay between retries. Default 1s.
- `PromptTemplates` (PromptTemplates) - Customizable prompt templates for build and validate operations.
- `Tools` ([]ToolConfig) - Tool configurations available to the agent during generation.
- `Skills` ([]string) - Named skills the agent should use (e.g., "code-generation", "refactoring", "testing").
- `ModelID` (string) - Optional model identifier override (e.g., "claude-sonnet-4-6", "gpt-4o"). Provider-specific.

### PromptTemplates

Customizable Go text/template strings for constructing agent prompts. Each field is optional; if empty, the default template for that operation is used.

Fields:
- `Build` (string) - Template for the build prompt. Available variables: `.ProjectIntent`, `.Intent`, `.Validations`, `.OutputDir`, `.DependencyNames`, `.GenerationID`.
- `Validate` (string) - Template for the LLM judge validation prompt. Available variables: `.Rubric`, `.ContextFiles`, `.GeneratedFiles`.
- `System` (string) - Optional system prompt prepended to all agent invocations.

### ToolConfig

Represents a tool available to the agent during generation.

Fields:
- `Name` (string) - Tool identifier (e.g., "bash", "file_read", "web_search").
- `Enabled` (bool) - Whether the tool is available. Default true.
- `Config` (map[string]any) - Tool-specific configuration parameters.

### SchemaVersion

A string enum tracking the spec file schema versions. Used for forward-compatible parsing and migration.

Values:
- `v1` - Current schema version for .ic and .icv files.

### SchemaViolation

Represents a single schema validation error found during spec file parsing.

Fields:
- `FilePath` (string) - Path to the file with the violation.
- `Field` (string) - The field name that failed validation (e.g., "name", "version", "validations[0].type").
- `Message` (string) - Human-readable description of the violation.
- `Severity` (string) - "error" or "warning". Errors prevent builds; warnings are informational.

## Constraints

- Core must have zero dependencies on other intentc packages.
- All types should be serializable to JSON and YAML (for state persistence).
- Error fields in serializable types must be strings, not error interfaces.
- Types should use value semantics where practical, pointer semantics for large structs passed across package boundaries (Target, Intent).
- AgentProfile must be fully serializable to YAML for config file storage.
